Solar Driver was heading to a local gas station for fuel delivery. He was on Interstate 25 Southbound in Albuquerque, NM when he struck a piece of road debris. This road debris punctured a hole in the saddle bag tank of his Tractor. Driver pulled over to check the damage near I-25 exit 221. At this time he sees the damage to the fuel tank and fuel leaking from it. He called 911 for help FD showed up in roughly 5 minutes and was able to patch the hole in the tank. Roughly 50 gallons was released onto the concrete and dirt where the unit was stopped. Once Solar Dispatch was contacted we dispatched Environmental Restoration to the scene for clean up. Once on site they determined the Fire Dept had cleaned the impacted concrete but the spill had migrated to the soil and roughly 30 feet down the hill that is in the area. The clean up crew deployed granular absorbents to soil to soak up any fuel and protect against any further migration. They also took soil samples at the site and determined the product seeped down 6 inches into the soil. Excavation of the area has been scheduled but Environmental Restoration and is going to take place on Thursday June 19th.
column170: Driver was trained on Smith System with focus on eye lead time. Also we are speaking with the tractor manufacturer to see if anything can be done to protect the tanks.

On May 07, 2025, A CN Mechanical employee observed liquid dripping from the bottom discharge cap of covered hopper car # SHPX432827 while performing rail car inspections on an outbound train at the Cn Stevens Point Wi. yard. The employee notified the on-duty transportation manager who in turn made all internal notifications to initiate a response to the incident. A CN emergency response contractor was dispatched to the location for inspection/ mitigation hopper car SHPX432827 (R) Last Contained Sodium Chlorate UN 1495, Class 5.1//PG II The CN contractor found the bottom discharge cap dripping product. The car was isolated for further investigation. The CN contractor secured the track by applying blue flag protection. The car was opened for internal inspection and found that the shipper failed to get all the liquid slurry removed, as well the camlock cap was not secured properly for shipment. The security seals were removed from the top hatch on SHPX432827 where the contractor noticed the liquid and product in the B end compartment, which was leaking out the bottom discharge. We will be solidifying the remaining product and off load the product into a highway container for disposal

column169: Hilco driver checked tank for water prior to loading, but failed to detect a small amount of water (improper preparation for transport). Driver loaded the hot asphalt product and left the facility. Roughly 20 minutes into his trip he noticed steam coming from the top of the trailer and immediately pulled over. As the steam came out of the vent pipe it siphoned product with the steam creating a boil over. Product did boil over for a few minutes and created a small spill of less than 25 gallons.
column170: Hilco management will take a more aggressive action to check tanks for water and further educate it's driving force in orientaion as well as driver meetings to check tanks for water.

column169: On May 15, 2025, at 1910 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar Inway personnel in Keller, Texas regarding the release of ABC FORMULA 300. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of 5.0 gallons of ABC FORMULA 300 (UN1760, 8, III) from (1) 275-gallon poly tote onto the trailer floor. The release was reportedly due to the cage rubbing against the plastic tote bladder and creating a hole in the tote, impacting a 26’ x 6’ area of the trailer floor. No drains or waterways were impacted by the release. The release was neutralized then cleaned with absorbents and the proper PPE. Contractors transferred the remaining product from the damaged tote into a new, clean tote and proceeded to shred the damaged tote. All waste generated from addressing this release was containerized in (2) 55-gallon DFs which were taken off-site by the contractor for proper disposal.

column169: On 5/15/2025 at approximately 1345, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 393838 at the ramp facility in Fort Worth, reporting undeclared dangerous goods.  The shipment is a 55 lb. plastic drum containing slow-dissolving chlorine tablets.  Using the active ingredient list on the drum, Dangerous Goods Administration obtained a generic safety data sheet that classified the commodity as UN2468.  The shipment was not prepared in accordance with IATA Regulations, missing the required markings, labeling, packaging, and paperwork.  The shipment is being held for an FAA investigation.

At 0114 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at terminal XDE. It was reported that approximately 15 gallons of "P70 Primer Weldon" were released from a metal drum due to improper loading and the lid of the drum coming loose. The release impacted the inside of trailer #3213270. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and determined that terminal personnel are capable of cleaning the release with PPE available on site. XPO will place the waste inside of a 20-gallon metal drum. ERTS generated waste ID 236623-1. The original drum will be shipped since it is not damaged.

column169: At 2237 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at terminal UDV. It was reported that approximately 1 oz of "ConvoClean Forte" was released from 2 plastic jugs due to a packaging defect. The release impacted the inside of trailer #3214872. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and determined that terminal personnel are not capable of cleaning the release with PPE available on site.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately (5) 2.5-gallons of UN1814 ConvoClean Fote product released to the wooden trailer floor and concrete dock floor impacting area 10’x10’ area. The contractors found multiple cartons on a pallet, must jugs were intact but the cartons were impacted. There were (5) drums generated, (1) 95-gallon poly drum containing damaged bottles, (1) 55-gallon poly drum with damaged bottles, (2) 55-poly drums containing damaged cardboard, and (1) 35-gallon poly drum with damaged cardboard. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: At 20:53 PM ET, UPO contacted the call center to report a spill that occurred inside of a trailer in Portland, OR. The spill consists of approximately 5 ounces of Houghto-Deox A-1714, which released from (1) 5-gallon metal drum due to not being properly strapped in prior to arrival, causing the material to spill out onto the trailer floor. The caller stated there may be other containers impacted as well. ERTS will dispatch a contractor to assist as this is a 5.1 material.   Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-cup of UN1505 Houghto-Deox A-1714 product released to the wooden trailer floor due to load shift. The contractors swept up the product and reported (3) of the pails were damaged. They generated (1) 55-gallon poly drum containing the damaged 5-gallon pails and floor sweepings. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: On May 13, 2025, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN3098 was punctured and released approximately ten (10) gallons of product to the trailer, freight, and terminal asphalt lot. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from EnviroServe (ES) to remediate the site. The crew containerized the damaged drum in one (1) 85-gallon metal overpack and utilized absorbents and hand tools to remediate the impacted areas. All impacted materials were containerized in one (1) 55-gallon drum for disposal.  On May 16, 2025, the crew returned to the site due to the chemical eating away at the overpack previously used. ES personnel placed the damaged drum of product into one (1) new 95-gallon poly drum. The old 85-gallon overpack was taken for disposal.

On 05/02/2025, at 16:35 hours, personnel in the CSXT Fostoria, Ohio Yard discovered SIRX525280, a loaded hopper car of Ferrous Sulfate, leaking from the A-end slide gate. The car was isolated and the shipper, SEM Minerals, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2025-05-02-00202).  SPSI, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the A-end slide gate open approximately 1-2” and spilling product. Contractor personnel applied plugging material to the slide gate door to secure the leak, as it could not be closed full.  The issue was identified, and corrective actions, were communicated to the shipper’s representative (Keith Mizwicki).

column169: On May 9, 2025, at 0954 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar Inway personnel in Kiptopeke, VA regarding the release of Sarnacol®-2170 VC Membrane Adhesive. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of approximately 1.0 cup of Sarnacol®-2170 VC Membrane Adhesive (UN1133, 3, II) from (1) 5-gallon plastic pail onto the trailer and asphalt. The release was reportedly due to the overtightening of a ratchet strap, impacting the trailer flatbed and asphalt. No drains or waterways were impacted by the release. The release was cleaned up with absorbents the proper PPE. Contractors removed the damaged pail from the trailer, placed it into an overpack, and re-secured the good product on the trailer flatbed. All waste generated from addressing this release was containerized in (2) 55-gallon DMs which were taken off-site by the contractor for proper disposal.

column169: AT BAY 490, A LEAKING FLAMMABLE LIQUID HAZMAT PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED. RESPONDER WAS NOTIFIED ABOUT IT FROM RMP AND HEADED HIS WAY WITH PPE ON, SPILL CART, AND CURRENT DECISION TREE. RESPONDER READ AND FOLLOWED CURRENT DECISION TREE, WHICH LED THEM TO THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET. RESPONDER READ AND FOLLOWED CURRENT FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET. SINCE THERE WAS NO LIQUID POURING OUT OF THE HAZMAT DIRECTLY, ZEP ZORBENT WAS NOT NEEDED. RESPONDER SUCCESSFULLY CONTAINED THE LEAKING FLAMMABLE LIQUID HAZMAT PACKAGE IN A SPILL TUB AND HEADED BACK TO THE PSC CAGE TO START PROCESSING IT. RESPONDER READ AND FOLLOWED CURRENT DISPOSAL WASTE FLOW CHART, WHICH LED THEM TO START THE DMP PROCEDURE. RESPONDER PUT THE LIQUID CONTAINERS INTO THE FIRST GREEN BAG. SINCE A CONTAINER CAP WAS DAMAGED, A CONTAINER HAD TO BE SOLIDIFIED WITH ZEP ZORBENT. THE CARDBOARD AND ZEP ZORBENT WAS PUT INTO A SECOND GREEN BAG. RESPONDER DECONTAMINATED THEIR PPE FOR THE NEXT SPILL PICKUP.

column43: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES CONTAINED IN EQUIPMENT INCLUDING LITHIUM ION POLYMER BATTERIES
column169: Customer came to pickup shipment in ANC and then ship it out again to SLC with some cargo he brought. I delivered it to him, he got the shipment ready to be shipped out to SLC, and then I started creating an AWB for him. I asked about any lithium batteries, he said yes and that his boss asked him to connect all the batteries to the tools when he received it. I found out that he had 5 lithium batteries in one container(toolbox), and he didn't know of the watts. He said the batteries were declared in DLG, we went and looked at the shipment and I did not see any UN 3481 labels on the container but there was a NOTOC label dated for today. Customer then opened up the shipment and looked at the watts, finding 1 lithium battery at 140wh. I advised that was over the allowed limit for shipping through Cargo and will have to take it out. He then went through another container(tote) and found 2 more spare lithium batteries by themselves. He had 4 tools total, I instructed he connect the batteries to the tools and separate to 2 tools per container. He took away 3 spare lithium batteries from the shipment, 1 of which was over the limit.    Customer was very pleasant throughout this experience and was very apologetic.
column170: Customer advised of the improper packaging and procedure for future shipments.

column169: Clean Harbors was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 10ft-by-40ft area of the trailer floor and estimated that five to ten (5-10) gallons of material was released due to forklift damaging one (1) 55-gallon metal drum. Clean Harbors deployed granular absorbents to the affected area of the trailer floor. The contractor overpacked the damaged drum into one (1) 65-gallon metal drum. The granular absorbents were gathered and containerized into two (2) 55-gallon metal drums. Clean Harbors labeled the containers and staged the generated waste before they demobilized. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

column169: t 1048 ET, XPO-XCW notified ERTS of a cargo release. It was reported that approximately 5 cups of phycomycin scp released from a plastic bag due to no dunnage. The release impacted inside trailer#319-1512 and the concrete dock. No storm drains or waterways are reported to be impacted by the release. ERTS will proceed to dispatch a contractor to the site to complete cleanup activities.   Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 3-cups of UN3378 Phycomycin SCP product was released to a 6’x2’ and 3’x1’ area of the wooden trailer floor due to improper loading (dunnage). The contractors swept up the spilled material and restacked the pallet and placed the impacted bag into (1) 55-gallon poly tote. The swept up product was containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: This was a return shipment of a lawnmower.  It was placed in the shipping box upside down and the gas cap was loose.  It leaked gasoline onto and in the shipping box and was noticed as it was being loaded into a trailer during the Outbound Sort.  it was brought to the hazmat cage.  Using FAST, we tried to locate a phone number for the shipper.  The phone number we found for Nematulah was disconnected.  We tried to find another phone number.  Numerous attempts at possible relatives proved futile.  All the phone numbers were disconnected and no longer in service.  We contacted Amerisun to see if they had a phone number for Nematulah based on the P.O. number on the barcode.  Amerisun said that even though they showed as the original shipper, they had no record of the P.O. and that it was purchased through a third party vendor and they had no information.

At 06:18 EST, ERTS was contacted by XPO (XDM) about a cargo release. It was reported that due to faulty packaging, approximately 8 ounces of Chem San 1400 (hazardous - UN1903) was released. The caller stated that the released product was contained to the top area near cap and did not impact the dock floor. The caller has requested a contractor to transfer the product into a new poly drum. There were no drains, soils or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed a small amount of material was observed around a drum’s bung cap were loose. The bung cap in question, along with three additional drum bung caps were secured. Each drum was staken to confirm integrity and no further issues were identified.

At 1425 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at terminal BGB. It was reported that an estimated 12) 2.5-gallon cardboard boxes w/ plastic bladder bags of UN1791 "Marketguard 121" released due to shipper error. The release impacted trailer. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and determined that terminal personnel are not capable of cleaning the release with PPE available on site.   Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 10 gallons UN1791 Marketguard 121 released to the trailer floor impacting 5’x5’ area due to load shift. The contractors cleaned the release with oil dri and generated (10) drums of waste (9) consisting of cardboard and damaged product and the 10th drum containing PPE. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: Hepaco was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 12ft-by-8ft area of the trailer floor and concrete dock and estimated that ten (10) gallons of material was released due to a forklift puncturing two (2) 5-gallon jerricans. Hepaco personnel removed all the freight from the trailer. Most of the product was at the nose of the trailer. The pH test revealed it was 0. Soda ash was deployed to neutralize the affected areas. The new pH reading for the trailer was 8-9. Three (3) 55-gallon poly drums were used to containerize empty jugs, impacted cardboard, bolts, fasteners, plastic wrap, absorbent pads, and PPE. Contractor personnel had to return to site because the terminal reported one of the drums reacted. All the drums were moved outside and filled with water under the supervision of the fire department. While Hepaco personnel waited for the temperature of the drums to cool down, they clean-up the affected concrete on the dock. The contents were contained into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum and filled with water. After the temperature of the drums lowered, the terminal manager and chief of fire department declared the site was safe to leave. The generated waste was staged onsite and will remain onsite for the Dayton Freight team to coordinate disposal.

AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT A METAL 5-GAL PAIL WAS BREACHED AND HAD LEAKED APPROX. 12 OUNCES OF THE LIQUID PRODUCT. THERE WAS NO INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL WITH ALOT OF ROOM FOR THE CONTAINER TO MOVE AROUND INSIDE OF THE CARTON. column169: At 21:42 PM ET, USA contacted the call center to report a spill that occurred inside of a trailer in Sacramento, CA. The spill consists of approximately half a gallon of Cetguard Thixo, which released from 3 1-gallon metal cans due to excessive freight stacked on top of the cans, crushing them and causing them to spill onto the trailer floor. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the terminal, and it was determined a contractor will be needed as a chemical respirator is required for cleanup.   Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-cups of UN1263 Cetcguard Thixo product released to the wooden trailer floor due to a load shift. They used absorbents to clean up and generated (1) 55-gallon metal drum containing spent absorbents and impacted debris. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

Amanda Linebarger, 120/ABQ operations supervisor, reported a 1 lb spill of UN1485, Potassium Chlorate, 5.1, II in the nose of trailer 553264 and a small amount at dock door 70. Amanda advised this spill was discovered while unloading and appeared to have happened in transit. 120/ABQ contained the sp ill and Cura has been contacted to send a crew to remediate the spill. Safety asked Cura to have the crew confirm the cause of the spill and the amount spilled. ER personnel unstacked the pallet of potassium chlorate and discovered five (5) damaged 55-pound bags. Crews utilized a HEPA vac to collect  all spilled material. All remaining freight was collecting into a cubic yard box for further handling by ABF. Crews collected five (5) damaged 55-pound bags of potassium chlorate into one (1) 55-gallon drum. All impacted PPE and debris were collected and containerized into one (1) 30-gallon drum. A ll collected waste was staged onsite for future transport and disposal by CES. Crews received site approval from Amanda Leinburg, secured the scene, and demobilized.

column169: Dayton Freight personnel observed approximately two (2) cups of material released from one (1) 263-gallon poly tote due to an unknown reason causing the tote to leak. column169: Environmental Services, Inc. (CT) was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 20ft-by-5ft area of the trailer and estimated that fifteen (15) gallons of material was released due to one (1) 15-gallon drum being damaged. Environmental Services, Inc. (CT) personnel observed that all the released material had dried. All freight was unloaded from the trailer by contractor personnel, and they deployed granular absorbents to the impacted area. The leaking drum was overpacked into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum and they secured the trailer. Contractor personnel followed the impacted truck to the nearest ESTES terminal located in Bellows Falls, VT. Environmental Services, Inc. (CT) then used three (3) 55-gallon poly drums to containerize the spent granular absorbents. All work was approved by the terminal supervisor after the contractor completed their clean-up. The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal

At approximately 1130 et as service tech was fixing a placard on the outside of the trailer he was using a drill to drill out the rivet to remove the damaged placard and ran the drill bit through the side of the trailer and into a drum inside the trailer. This resulted in a small hole in the side of the drum allowing the material to slowly leek out. absorbent and a containment was placed under trailer. They then call our internal response team to address the leaking container. The team showed up at 1300et to proceed with the clean up. They dawned the proper ppe and began unloading the trailer to gain access to the drum. Once they gained access the drum was placed into a salvage container and the material that had been released was cleaned up using absorbents and placed into the salvage container for disposal. The team was complete at 1700et.
column170: The use of a drill to remove a rivet in the sidewall of the trailer should not have been done on a loaded trailer and will be addressed. They will have to check and verify that the trailer is empty and safe to due so before performing any maintenance on the equipment.

column169: Hepaco was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 4in-by-4in area of the concrete dock floor and estimated that six (6) ounces of material were released due to a damaged valve and puncture in one (1) 2583-pound metal tote. Hepaco personnel determined a tote transfer would be needed. Hepaco wiped down the tote and started the tote transfer. They used a gravity transfer for the tote transfer to one (1) poly tote. No waste was generated from the cleanup or the tote transfer. Hepaco personnel staged the new tote on-site and set aside the damaged tote for Dayton to send back to the shipper, INX Lebanon.

column169: On 5/8/2025 at 1:50 PM, Canadian Pacific Kansas City Railroad (CPKC) Hazmat Department became aware that FRA  Inspector Daniel Perkins had performed a hazmat inspection at the CPKC Milwaukee, WI rail yard. During the inspection, Mr. Perkins detected an odor upon opening the protective housing cover on residue tank car FURX 134030. Mr. Perkins also detected a hissing sound coming from the B-end liquid valve assembly plug region.  Mr. Perkins turned the B-end liquid valve handle approximately one inch in the closed direction. The hissing noise gradually ended, and the detected odor began to dissipate.  Additionally, Mr. Perkins found the A-end liquid valve plug, and vapor valve plug less than tool tight.   A railroad qualified response contractor was mobilized to correct any defects. The A-end liquid valve plug, and vapor valve plug were secured tool tight.  All other closures were verified to be properly secured.  The shipper was notified and instructed to obtain an OTMA-1 to move the FURX 134030 to home shop for requalification.    File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at the time of filing.  This shipment was offered as a 'bulk' shipment, aka one car load, therefore the exact amount offered in this package is not known to the carrier. This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantify this value.
column170: The SOO LINE RAILROAD COMPANY (DBA CPKC) notified shipper of this release. Continued emphasis with Offerors/Shippers is made to conduct thorough inspections prior to movement in order to reduce valve failures in the field. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with SOO Line Railroad (Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Ed Dankbar, SOO Line Railroad, 120 S 6th ST STE 900, Minneapolis, MN 55402. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column169: On 05-28-2025 a CN transportation employee observed a white liquid running down the side of tank car UTLX 682906 (loaded/UN 2215/Class 8 PG III) while performing switching operations at the CN Baton Rouge Yard in Baton Rouge, LA. Emergency notification was made to the CN Dangerous Goods Team, who responded to the incident. The CN Dangerous Goods Officer noted a significant amount of solidified white product on the sides of the tank car emanating from within the closed protective housing upon arrival. The protective housing was found to be completely full of solidified product, with a small stream of liquid still leaking, making it impossible to locate the origin of the leak. The manway cover swing bolts were loosened in order to relieve the internal pressure, which stopped the leak. The solidified product from within the protective housing was removed by use of a pneumatic chipping hammer and hot water pressure washer. All fittings within the protective housing were found to be secure. As the car was no longer leaking, it was impossible to determine the origin of the leak. The car remains in hold at the Baton Rouge Yard until the shipper receives an FRA OTMA 1 to have the car returned to the shippers' facility in Geismar, LA.

column43: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column169: A three pallet/package shipment was identified as containing undeclared dangerous goods at the FedEx origin station in Jamaica, New York after being transported by surface transport from the station in Newark, New Jersey. When more than two Cordless Robot Pool Cleaners were visible on a single pallet in a consignment of more than two packages, employees noted the lack of 3481 Lithium battery marks on the outer packaging and reported the issue to Dangerous Goods Administration. The shipment was opened to determine the quantities of UN3481 per pallet and audit the contents after it was noted that the Commercial Invoice listed several suspicious entries. Numerous additional UN3481s were discovered along with other undeclared regulated DG contained in the three pallets (flammable aerosols and UN3480s). This shipment has been deemed to be undeclared based on the existence of 2.1s and UN3480s being in this shipment with no indication of their inclusion. The Master Tracking number 880927791184 (and subsidiary tracking numbers 880927791195 and 880927791200) contained a total of 143 inner containers of UN3481, 281 inner containers of flammable aerosol sunscreen, 10 inner containers of flammable aerosol insecticide and 3 stand-alone lithium ion batteries, 1 of which appears to be over 100 watt-hour capacity. The origin station was directed by FedEx Dangerous Goods Administration to hold the shipment pending further disposition instructions.

Bryan Youtzy, 042 Operations Supervisor, contacted Safety regarding multiple hazard class spills on the trailer floor. Bryan Youtzy advised the spill appears to be caused by improper loading. Bryan Youtzy stated the freight was loaded on bars of the bulkhead and the freight slid forward while in-tra nsit. Bryan Youtzy advised due to the spill on the trailer floor and the freight being loaded on the bars, he's unable to locate the pros spilling. Bryan Youtzy advised the spill on the trailer wall as well. Safety reviewed what pros are loaded on the trailer and approximately 19 hazardous pros of S igma-Aldrich are loaded within the trailer. Safety advised Bryan Youtzy that CURA will be contacted for remediation. Safety contacted Cameron Kerr with CURA for remediation. FCE personnel noted six (6) damaged one-gallon jugs of UN1789 with approximately one gallon of product released to the trailer  floor. An on-site RLC forklift was utilized to unload the trailer onto a poly sheeting staging area for better access to the spill. Crews utilized cleaners and absorbent pads to remove all free-standing product. The damaged jugs, all UN1789 impacted materials, and spent absorbents were collected an d containerized into three (3) 55-gallon drums and five (5) five-gallon pails for disposal. The drums were properly labeled and staged on-site for further management.

Holly stated that the substance appeared to be a white powder located on top of the lids of the pails. She mentioned that she could not  see any visible damage to the pails, as they were wrapped in plastic. However, it appeared that some of the lids had shifted, causing a few to become loose or pop off. Holly estimated that the pails were approximately 55 lbs each, and that there was about 8 ounces of the white powder on the lids.~~ CURA was called to assist with the spill in the trailer.

A GROUP OF PACKAGES THAT WERE WET FROM RAINWATER, AND AMONG THEM A FULLY REGULATED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WERE DISCOVERED BY THE SWEEPER IN UNLOAD-E. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN 2 MINUTES A DESIGNATED RESPONDER ARRIVED, DONNING THE PROPER PPE AND WITH A FULLY STOCKED SPILL CART. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET, THE HAZ-MAT WAS CONTAINED AND SEGREGATED, WITH THE CARTON SHOWING WETTNESS, BUT NO SIGNS OF SPILLAGE, THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 2 POLY 1-LB CONTAINERS WAS LOOSE BY A COUPLE OF ROTATIONS, CAUSING A COUPLE OF OUNCES OF THE PRODUCT TO LEAK OUT OF THE BREACH AND REMAIN CONFINED INTERNALLY IN THE BASE OF THE CARTON. THE PACKING MATERIAL CONSISTED OF 2" OR MORE OF KRAFT PAPER AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A SINGLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 32 LBS/IN EDGE CRUSH TEST (ECT).

column169: On May 15, 2025, at 1215 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar Ranger personnel in Washington, MO regarding the release of Ethanol. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of 275.0 gallons of Ethanol (UN1170, 3, II) from (1) 270-gal poy tote and (1) 5-gal plastic pail onto asphalt and the trailer floor. The release was reportedly due to a load shift as the tote slid into a pallet, impacting the trailer floor and a 1’ x 2’ area of asphalt. No drains or waterways were impacted by the release. The release was cleaned up with absorbents and the proper PPE. Damaged pails of product were overpacked in a flex bin by the contractors to leave with the consignee and send back to the shipper. All waste generated from addressing this release was containerized in (2) 55-gallon DGs which were taken off-site by the contractor pending proper disposal.

column169: AT APPROXIMATELY 17:30 THE SUPERVISOR FROM UNLOAD B CALLED DMP ABOUT A LEAKING PACKAGE IN DOOR 15. A DESIGNATED RESPONDER DONNED ALL APPROPRIATE PPE AND RETRIEVED A FULLY STOCKED SPILL CART. AFTER ARRIVING ON SCENE, THE RESPONDER NOTICED A HAZMAT PACKAGE WITH MOISTURE SEEPING OUT OF ONE OF THE CORNERS OF THE PACKAGE. THE RESPONDER THEN REFERRED TO THEIR DECISION TREE AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET AND ACTED ACCORDINGLY. AFTER CLEANING UP ALL SPILL DEBRIS THE PACKAGE WAS TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE DMP CAGE FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. UPON OPENING THE SINGLEWALL FIBREBOARD BOX IT WAS DISCOVERED THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS A PUNTURE HOLE IN THE BODY OF THE CONTAINER. THE PACKAGE WAS FINALLY DISPOSED OF ACCORDING TO THE DMP WASTE DISPOSAL FLOW CHART.

column169: On May 12, 2025, nineteen (19) 1-gallon pails of paint (PG II) and one (1) 4-gallon pail of paint (PG II) were damaged by a forklift and released approximately 15-20 gallons of product to the trailer interior, pallets, and nearby freight. The 1-gallon pails damaged include SHER-WOOD Color Express Precat Matte White Tint Base (3 pails), KEM 400 Enamel Blending Clear (8 pails), Polane T Polyurethane Enamel Blending Clear (8 pails). The one (1) damaged 4-gallon pail included POLANE B Polyurethane Enamel (Part A) Clear (PG II). R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Environmental Safety and Health Consulting Services (ES&H) to remediate the site. All of the damaged pails and the remaining product in the pails were containerized and solidified using absorbents within one (1) 55-gallon drum. The crew utilized absorbent pads and granular absorbents to remove the paint from the trailer interior and adjacent freight, which were containerized in the previously mentioned 55-gallon drum. The impacted pallets were dismantled and containerized in one (1) additional 55-gallon drum.

column169: As a dockworker was unloading a trailer, he noticed that pallets were double stacked in front of the hazmat shipment. There was no dunnage used to separate the stacked pallet from the hazmat.  As the shipment rode to its destination, the movement of the trailer caused the pallet to dig into the hazmat bags and rip them. The damaged bags were removed and placed in a plastic overpack container.  All other spilled materials were cleaned up and placed in an overpack containers in preparation for disposition.

column169: On 5/7/2025 at approximately 1145, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 294822 at the ramp facility in Anchorage, reporting undeclared dangerous goods.  The shipment consisted of 6 fiberboard boxes, each containing several mobile phones.  Each box yielded an estimated gross weight of 56.5 kg, which leads to the presumption that the packages should have possibly been classified as fully regulated UN 3481 Section I.  None of the packages appear to be prepared in accordance with IATA Regulations as they do not display the required markings, labeling, packaging or paperwork.  The shipment will be set for disposal.

column169: On May 28, 2025, six (6) 5-gallon pails of HS Enamel New Casella Blue (UN1263) were crushed in transit and released approximately two (2) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from ES+ to remediate the impacted site. ES+ personnel collected the six (6) damaged pails of paint and containerized them in two (2) 55-gallon drums. The crew then utilized granular absorbents and hand tools to remediate the trailer interior. All impacted materials were containerized in one (1) additional 55-gallon drum for future disposal.

FRA Inspector found UTLX 673138 with dry product residue around the bottom outlet valve. No ground contact. No waterways or sewers impacted.  BNSF Hazmat (J. Hankins) responded to car and found some dried product around BOV nozzle. Cap was less than tool-tight. Valve was closed. Upon removing cap a small amount of liquid was noted inside cap and no visible leakage occurring past the ball valve. Gasket looked to be in good shape, but was replaced with a new gasket. Cap was replaced and tool-tightened.

column169: On 5/1/2025 at approximately 15:45 FedEx DG Administration was notified of an undeclared dangerous goods spill at Toledo, OH station. column169: At approximately 0930 ct when the driver was unloading his truck he punctured drum with the forks of the forklift. There was approximately 20 gallons released to the back of the truck and onto the pavement under the unit. There were no waterway or soil impacted. Absorbent was immediately put in place and the drum was placed into a salvage container. The total time of the incident was about 20 minutes. We did call our internal response team to address the release area with a thorough cleaning and all absorbents that were used were placed into the appropriate container for disposal. Final clean up was complete by 1300 ct.
column170: The driver was retrained on the proper use of the forklift.

At 15:54 ET, XPO notified the Call Center of a cargo release at a customer location in Chaska, MN. It was reported that approximately 5 gallons of Vanilla Extract released from one 5-gallon pail due to being punctured by the customer while unloading the trailer. The release impacted trailer #4632581. No storm drains or waterways are reported to be impacted by the release.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 5-gallons of UN1197 Vanilla Extract product released to a 40’x6’ area of the trailer floor and the asphalt lot below due to forklift puncture. The contractors used absorbents for cleanup and overpacked the waste and damaged pail and restacked the pallet for shipping. There were (2) poly drums, (1) 5-gallon and (1) 30-gallon. They used a degreaser to help bring up as much product as possible. The waste was taken off site and staged at vendors office for disposal.

At 00:11 AM ET, Morgan with UDV contacted the call center to request assistance with a spill that occurred inside of a trailer in Henderson, CO. The spill consists of approximately 10 ounces of Infused, which released from a 1 275-gallon plastic tote due to a loose lid that caused the product to slosh around and spill on the top of the tote and on the trailer floor. ERTS will dispatch a contractor to assist, as this is a corrosive liquid inside of a tote. No SDS could be located for this product.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 10-ounces of UN3264 Infused product released from a 275-gallon plastic tote to the top of the tote and an area of the wooden trailer floor (4’x4’) due to improper packaging & a loose cap. The crew used absorbents to collect and containerize the spill and generated (1) 5-pound poly drum containing impacted absorbents and PPE. Absorbents were then deployed and worked into the  impacted areas. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: At 0957 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at terminal XSO. It was reported that an unknown amount of battery acid UN2794 released from industrial battery due. The release impacted Door 9.  ERTS will proceed to dispatch a contractor to the site to complete cleanup activities.   XPO-XSO contacted ERTS regarding a large battery that tipped over in transit releasing battery acid onto the  trailer floor and dock floor. A contractor dispatched and observed an estimated 5-gallon release onto the entire  wooden trailer floor and an estimated 25-foot area on the concrete dock floor as a result of a load shift /  inadequate preparation for transportation. The contractor applied baking soda and oil dry to the release and  up righted the battery. One 55-gallon DF containing the neutralized spent absorbents and impacted shrink  wrap was generated for waste disposal. The Shipper does not want the batter back, so that was also labelled  for waste disposal. XPO will manage all waste created from the response. No storm-drains, waterways, or soil  were involved in this incident.

column169: On May 9, 2025. at 07:30 I've received a call from our driver. He noticed that there was a leak coming from a front end of the trailer and immediately called our office. The driver told me he was going to delivery at 15780 Alamo Jct. Elmendorf, TX 78112, he missed the left turn towards the Alamo Jct. (coming from the north on Richter Rd) and kept going south on Richter Rd and did a multipoint turn. That's where the load shifted and one of the IBCs got punctured by dunnage (wooden pallet, hole size 2 by 4) that shipper loaded up all the way in front of the trailer. A leak started and the driver called us immediately.  If the shipper didn't load us with dunnage at the front of the trailer, the broken dunnage (pallet) wouldn't puncture the IBC even with the load shift that occurred. The duration of release was approximately 3hrs.  No injuries or other damage were reported. I called Chemtrec (ER contact) and they advised me to call the Receiver (Univar) because they were just 20 yards down the road to have them try to contain the spill. On-site Univar Solutions personnel deployed granular absorbents and soda ash to contain and neutralize the release. Additionally, an 85-gallon drum was placed under the leaking tote to provide further containment until crews arrived. At approximately 8:29 AM CDT, a representative from Univar Solutions (US) retained Cura Emergency Services, L.C. (CES) to manage the environmental remediation of the site on their behalf. Based on the available information, the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from Lone Star Hazmat (LSH) to assess and remediate the site as necessary.
column170: Two major things that contributed to this spill were: 1: Driver's fault in which he went off the road to make a multi-point turn where the load shifted towards the front. 2: Stack of wooden pallets that were used as dunnage to offset the weight towards the center of the trailer.  On our end we will use this incident for training purposes and have the drivers trained on all the hazards and potential hazards that could drastically increase the probability of cargo damage/spill, so it won't reoccur again in the future.  Shipper should improve the safety awareness of how wrong load securement/bracing can endanger safety of the load and integrity of the containers loaded. Wooden pallets should not be used as dunnage because in case of minor load shift, they are first to be crushed by weight of the IBCs and first to puncture those IBCs like in this incident.

On 05/07/2025, a CN transportation employee observed liquid on the side of tank car # DPRX 258989 (Loaded / UN 1117 / Class 3) at the CN Flat Rock Yard located in Flat Rock, MI. Internal emergency response notifications were made to further investigate. The assessment of the tank car revealed that all 6 manway cover swing bolts were found to be less than tool-tight (easily turned by a gloved hand), preventing a proper seal of the manway cover, allowing the contents to leak during transportation. The manway cover was opened for gasket integrity inspection. The manway cover gasket was found to be intact without any noticeable defects. The manway cover swing bolts were properly tightened with a 24' pipe wrench.

column59: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column169: An odor was reported by UPRR yard personnel at 0732 in Livonia LA on 5-2-2025. Hazardous Materials Manager Tom Robinson was called for a response. Manager Robinson found AXLX 967 leaking from the pressure relief device at a very slow rate. The car was isolated in the haz mat track. HMM Robinson and a contractor used the crows foot wrench from the C-kit and tried to tighten the PRD mounting bolts. We were able to get a small turn on one of the bolts, however we thought the leak continued. The capping kit was applied to what we believed was a broken pressure relief device. The car was monitored for 48 hours and there was no pressure inside the can with the capping kit applied. A verbal OTMA was given to UPRR from Mark Maday with the FRA to move the car on ULIALR 4 on 5-4-2025. The car was delivered to Westlake at 2015 hours on 5-4-2025.

column169: attachment Name:ZEP PURPLE DEGREASER 1 GAL SDS.pdf

On May 23, 2025, one (1) 330-gallon tote of E-Pure MSA (UN3265) was punctured by a forklift and released approximately ten (10) ounces of product to the loading dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Lewis Environmental Group (LEG) to remediate the impacted site. The crew conducted a tote transfer into one (1) new 330-gallon tote for continued shipment, then dismantled the damaged tote for disposal. LEG personnel utilized granular absorbents, absorbent pads, cleaning agents, and hand tools to remediate the site. The dismantled tote and all impacted materials were containerized in one (1) 55-gallon drum for disposal.

column169: At 0453 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at terminal LDA. It was reported that approximately 2 gallons of Tractor Equipment Enamel Paint was released from two 1-gallon metal pails due to improper packaging by terminal LDA. The release impacted trailer # 3233474. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and they felt comfortable cleaning up the release with PPE available on-site. Will need to call Chemtrec. 239124-1 – 10-gallon DM contains two 1-gallon metal pails of Tractor Equipment Enamel Paint and oil dri.

At 0116 EDT on 5/3, XPO-XCA contacted ERTS to report a spill of about 1 cup of "Benzoyl Chloride" from a 55-gal poly drum onto the trailer and dock floors. The drum was loaded with a faulty seal and is spilling in motion. XPO personnel cannot handle the class 8 material. ERTS will dispatch a contractor to assist. ERTS reported the spill to Chemtrec and spoke to Alan who provided report number: 2025050300007.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-cup of UN1736 Benzoyl Chloride product released to the top and sides of the poly drum impacting area 2’x2’ area due to improper packaging – bad seal on the bung cap. The contractors replaced the bung cap with a new one, and did a shake test. The crew removed the shrink wrap off the drum and wiped it down. (1) 55-poly drum was generated containing impacted PPE, absorbent rags, and shrink wrap. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

Forklift driver punctured 1 tote when moving freight. Maree Montoya, 120/ABQ Operations Supervisor,  reported 330 Gallons from 1 tote spilled on dock floor due to a forklift operator puncturing the tote. A crew from Environmental Restoration arrived. Crews placed absorbent pads and absorbent booms t o contain the release on the loading dock. Environmental Restoration personnel utilized a shop-vac to collect freestanding liquid throughout the release site.  Environmental Restoration personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted area and worked them in with hand tools. Crews utilized a s hop-vac to transfer the remaining contents of the damaged tote into 55-gallon drums. All alcoholic beverage-impacted material was collected and containerized in five (5) 55-gallon drums and staged on-site for further management. ER personnel noted no further actions required on-site and crews demobi lized.

column169: At 08:49 EST, ERTS was contacted by XPO (XOW) about a cargo release. It was reported that due to improper loading, approximately 1 gallon of Chemlife 24 Coating (hazardous - UN1263) was released. The caller stated that the released product was contained to the trailer floor. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and they felt comfortable cleaning the release donning the proper PPE per SDS. The released product, damaged pail, and oil-dri will be placed into a 55-gallon metal drum and staged in OS&D. There were no drains, soils or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release. There is no regulatory reporting required for this release. ERTS will upload the BOL, SDS and create a waste container entry.
attachment Name:Hazmat- Damaged Haz Mat Package Disposition 04302024.pdf

At 1031 EST, ERTS was contacted by Jack Martin of XPO Logistics (UPO) about a cargo release. It was reported that due to improper loading, approximately .25 teaspoon of Oxidate 5.0 (hazardous - UN3109) was released. The caller stated that the released product was contained to the shrink wrap only as condensation. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and they felt comfortable cleaning the release donning the proper PPE per SDS. The vented cap was tightened on the jug and sent to the Consignee, and the impacted shrink wrap was paced into a 20-gallon poly drum and staged in OS&D. There were no drains, soils or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release. There is no regulatory reporting required for this release.   Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately ¼ tsp of UN3109 Oxidate 5.0 product released due to improper loading. The contractors opened and placed the drum which XPO had created into a vented 55-gallon poly drum and submerged the impacted shrink wrap with water. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.
attachment Name:Hazmat- Damaged Haz Mat Package Disposition 04302024.pdf

AT THE UPS FACILITY IN GOODYEAR, ARIZONA, ONE AIR PACKAGE BROKE OPEN. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS DISCOVERED NUMEROUS UNSECURED PANASONIC CR2032 LITHIUM METAL COIN CELLS WITHIN THE BOX. MOST OF THE SMALL COIN CELLS ARE IN PLASTIC HOLDERS DESIGNED TO HOLD TWO CELLS EACH WITH THE CELLS OPENLY EXPOSED. NUMEROUS CELLS ARE LOOSE WITHIN THE BOX WITHOUT THEIR PLASTIC HOLDERS. THERE IS NO PROTECTION AGAINST SHORT CIRCUIT. NO ENCLOSURES SURROUNDING THE COIN CELLS. NO ADDITIONAL INNER PACKAGING. THERE ARE NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER BOX TO INDICATE REGULATED DANGEROUS GOODS ARE WITHIN THE BOX. PRIOR TO THE UNDECLARED DISCOVERY, THE PACKAGE WAS FLOWN ON UPS AIRCRAFT FROM SDF TO PHX. THE PACKAGE WAS SHIPPED FROM ILLINOIS USING UPS ACCOUNT NUMBER H1A865, AMERICAN SCIENCE   SURPLUS, 7410 N LEHIGH AVE, NILES IL 60714-4024.

column169: Clean Harbors was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted two areas of trailer floor with the dimensions a 3 ft x 3 ft and 1 ft x 2 ft and estimated that one (1) gallon of material was released due to a puncture in one (1) poly tote. Clean Harbors performed a tote transfer to one (1) 275-gallon poly tote and two (2) 55-gallon poly drums that was sent on to the customer. The contractor neutralized the trailer floor that was impacted. Clean harbors removed a 4' by 5' area of flooring for repair. They cut up the damaged tote and cage containerizing it into three (3) 55-gallon poly drums. Two (2) flex bins with cut up tote and wood were also generated. The waste was staged onsite, and ESTES approved of cleanup activities. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

On May 27, 2025, Approximately 50-gallons diesel were released to the concrete and asphalt due to a fuel. overfill, while offloading. The release impacted asphalt and concrete on their tank pad. No storm drains or waterways are reported to be impacted by the release. A clean up contractor (Hepaco of Birmingham, AL) responded to the site to conduct cleanup activities. Absorbent material was applied the affected concrete and asphalt, using hand tools to spread and ensure absorption. The saturated absorbents were collected and containerized into (2) 55-gallon drums that were transported off site for proper disposal.  On June 13, 2025, two 55-gallon drums containing non-hazardous solid waste, (diesel impacted absorbents and boom), were accepted at Clean Harbors of Chattanooga, TN for proper disposal.  This was a one-time event, that was an immediate release, due to human error. Clean-up activities were completed the same day. This release has been completely remediated, and no evidence was found that suggests any significant environmental impact remains on site.

At 0523 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at terminal XAC. It was reported that approximately 2-cups of Sodium Carbonate Peroxyhydrate released from a plastic bag due to unknown reasons. The release impacted inside of trailer #55413340. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and determined that terminal personnel are not capable of cleaning the release with PPE available on site  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-cups of UN3378 Sodium Carbonate Peroxyhydrate product released to a 2’x3’ area of the wooden trailer floor due to improper loading. The contractors utilized a HEPA vacuum to collect the dry powder and containerized the waste into a 55-gallon poly drum along with (1) bag of product and PPE. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.
One 55 pound paper bag was torn at seam due to faulty packaging, released 2 ounces in trailer.

column169: The cleanup crew arrived onsite.  The spill area on the concrete sidewalk was approximately 4' x 8' and along the curb for approximately 20'.  The diesel fuel had migrated along the curb and then a small amount entered a storm drain.  It was reported that approximately two (2) table spoons of diesel fuel had exited the storm drain and into the river.  The site personnel had cleaned up most of the concrete.  The crew sprayed MicroBlaze on the spots of diesel and then placed clay absorbents down and worked them around with brooms.  The absorbents were collected and placed into a 55-gallon drum.  Site personnel had placed absorbent boom across the river to catch floating sheen.

column169: TILX112017 was found leaking hydrochloric acid on Track 4W in Deerfield Yard.  At approximately 2100 hours, Hepaco LLC, mobilized to site with three technicians, one supervisor, and one pickup truck.  Hepaco LLC arrived onsite at 2330 hours and conducted safety briefing, received track protection.  Hepaco worked with railroad and shipper to approve corrections.  At 0200 hours TILX112017 tank car was corrected and secured.  Hepaco secured area and decontaminated equipment that was used.  Apparent cause of incident concluded (Liquid Line A was less than tool tight, Liquid Line B was missing a gasket on the blind flange, and there were multiple gaskets on vapor line flange.  Gasket installed on flange, flange secured, and security seals attached.
column170: Shipper to improve operating procedures so that tank car is adequate for safe transportation.

column169: On May 20th, 2025, at 0609 hours, personnel in the CSXT Russell Yard discovered PROX90809, a loaded tank car of Anhydrous Ammonia, leaking from the top of car. The car was isolated and the shipper, PCS Sales Inc., was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #0520-2025-00044). Quick Response, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found ammonia vapor actively releasing from the pressure relief valve (PRV). Additional response personnel installed a Midland capping kit over the leaking PRD to contain the release. The car was then trans-loaded, nitrogen purged, and prepped for home shop.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative- Matt Paynter (706-564-8118).

column169: Employees were in the process of offloading drums that had been picked up from a household waste location in North Las Vegas. As an employee was attempting to place a drum onto a pallet it "exploded" and the lid and bolt ring struck an employeee's hands, forearms and head. Another employee had removed the drum from the trailer and according to him there was no evidence of bulging or other indication the contents were under pressure prior to the incident.   The drum's contents included aersols and lighters, which the customer's employees should not have packaged together.
column170: Training will be provided to the customer's employees on proper packaging of aersols.

column169: One 05/22/2025, at approximately 13:05 hours, an FRA inspector at the CSX yard in Portland, Maine, discovered tank car GATX 201284, load of Liquefied Petroleum Gas, was leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Blue Racer Midstream, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report 2025-05-22-0012).  Additionally, the South Portland Fire Department and Maine Department of Environmental Protection were notified.  Fire department personnel responded and found the cause of the release was the tank car’s Liquid line valve was partially open and the secondary securement plug was less than tool tight.  Fire department personnel closed the valve to stop the release.  HEPACO, a CSX emergency response contractor, was also dispatched to the incident to conduct a secondary inspection and ensure the car was properly secured for transportation. The issue was identified, and corrective actions, were communicated to the shipper’s representative
